-- 15-recursive-explanation.cell (v0.2)
-- Explains a concept. Identifies hardest sub-concepts. Explains each.
-- Recurses until all leaf explanations pass a comprehension oracle.
--
-- Tests: ‚äĘ‚äĘ spawner (recursive tree, accumulate mode), ‚äĘ‚ąė evolution loop,
--        comprehension oracle ("would a 10-year-old understand?"),
--        recursive depth controlled by semantic judgment,
--        wildcard deps, file-scope ‚ä®?, given? for ‚ä•-tolerance
--
-- v0.2 changes from R16:
--   - Added file-scope ‚ä®? recovery policy (retry max 3, then ‚ä•)
--   - ‚äĘ‚äĘ spawn-explainers: explicit `accumulate` (spawned sub-explainers
--     persist across ‚äĘ‚ąė iterations ‚ÄĒ tree grows monotonically)
--   - Wildcard deps (explainer-*‚Üífield) now formally spec-compliant
--   - Oracles on ‚äĘ‚ąė-managed cell (explain) are aspirational, not gates
--   - ‚äĘ‚ąė parameter binding: concept‚Üítext as fixed context across iterations
--   - Guard clause on deepen: only fires when remaining-hard is non-empty
--   - given? on collect-explanations for ‚ä•-tolerant assembly
--
-- Concept: "How does Cell's confluence property work and why does it matter?"

‚ä®? on failure:
  retry with ¬ęoracle.failures¬Ľ appended to prompt
  max 3 attempts
‚ä®? on exhaustion:
  error-value(‚ä•)

‚äĘ concept
  given text ‚Č° "How does Cell's confluence property work and why does it matter?"
  yield text

  ‚ä® text names a concept that can be explained at multiple levels of depth

‚äĘ explain
  given concept‚Üítext
  yield explanation, jargon-terms[]

  ‚ąī Explain ¬ęconcept‚Üítext¬Ľ clearly and completely. Use plain language where
    possible but don't sacrifice accuracy. After writing the explanation,
    list every technical term or concept you used that a non-expert might
    not understand (the "jargon terms"). These are candidates for recursive
    explanation.

  -- [aspirational under ‚äĘ‚ąė ‚ÄĒ these guide improvement, not gate freezing]
  ‚ä® explanation addresses both "how it works" and "why it matters"
  ‚ä® explanation is 3-8 sentences
  ‚ä® length(jargon-terms) ‚Č• 1

‚äĘ assess-comprehension
  given explain‚Üíexplanation
  given explain‚Üíjargon-terms
  yield clear-terms[], hard-terms[], comprehension-score

  ‚ąī For each jargon term in ¬ęexplain‚Üíjargon-terms¬Ľ, judge:
    Would a curious 10-year-old understand this term from context in the
    explanation ¬ęexplain‚Üíexplanation¬Ľ?

    Clear: the explanation provides enough context to understand the term
    (e.g., "list" in "a list of items" ‚ÄĒ self-evident).
    Hard: the term requires its own explanation (e.g., "topological sort"
    ‚ÄĒ not self-evident from context).

    Pick the 3 hardest terms (most opaque, most crucial to understanding).
    Score comprehension 0-10: how well would a 10-year-old understand
    the full explanation?

  ‚ä® length(clear-terms) + length(hard-terms) = length(explain‚Üíjargon-terms)
  ‚ä® length(hard-terms) ‚Č§ 3
  ‚ä® comprehension-score ‚ąą [0, 10]
  ‚ä® if comprehension-score ‚Č• 9 then hard-terms is empty

‚äĘ‚äĘ spawn-explainers
  given assess-comprehension‚Üíhard-terms
  given ¬ßsub-explain-template
  yield ¬ßexplainer-cells[]
  until length(explainer-cells) = length(assess-comprehension‚Üíhard-terms)
  max 5
  accumulate

  ‚ąī For each hard term in ¬ęassess-comprehension‚Üíhard-terms¬Ľ, spawn an
    explainer cell that explains just that term at a 10-year-old's level.
    Each spawned cell receives the term and the parent explanation as context.

  ‚ä® length(explainer-cells) = length(assess-comprehension‚Üíhard-terms)

‚äĘ sub-explain-template
  given term
  given parent-context
  yield explanation, still-hard

  ‚ąī Explain ¬ęterm¬Ľ so a curious 10-year-old could understand it.
    Use analogies, examples, and everyday language. The term appeared in
    this context: ¬ęparent-context¬Ľ. Your explanation should make that
    context comprehensible.

    After explaining, judge: does YOUR explanation introduce any term a
    10-year-old wouldn't understand? If yes, mark still-hard = true.

  ‚ä® explanation uses no unexplained jargon
  ‚ä® explanation is 2-5 sentences
  ‚ä® explanation uses at least one analogy or concrete example
  ‚ä® still-hard ‚ąą {true, false}

‚äĘ collect-explanations
  given explain‚Üíexplanation
  given assess-comprehension‚Üíclear-terms
  given explainer-*‚Üíexplanation
  given explainer-*‚Üístill-hard
  yield full-explanation, remaining-hard[], leaf-score

  ‚ąī Assemble a complete explanation by combining:
    1. The main explanation: ¬ęexplain‚Üíexplanation¬Ľ
    2. Sub-explanations for each hard term from the explainer cells

    Format as a layered explanation: main text first, then "What does X
    mean?" sections for each sub-explained term.

    Check: are any explainer cells still-hard = true? If so, those terms
    need further recursion. Compute leaf-score:
    - 10 if no remaining hard terms
    - Lower proportional to remaining hard terms

  ‚ä® full-explanation includes the main explanation and all sub-explanations
  ‚ä® remaining-hard contains only terms where still-hard = true
  ‚ä® leaf-score = 10 if remaining-hard is empty

‚äĘ deepen
  given collect-explanations‚Üíremaining-hard where len(remaining-hard) > 0
  given collect-explanations‚Üífull-explanation
  yield deeper-explanations[]

  ‚ąī For each still-hard term in ¬ęcollect-explanations‚Üíremaining-hard¬Ľ,
    provide a simpler explanation using only words a 10-year-old knows.
    Use analogies from everyday life. No technical terms allowed.

  ‚ä® each deeper explanation uses only everyday language
  ‚ä® each deeper explanation includes an analogy
  ‚ä® length(deeper-explanations) = length(collect-explanations‚Üíremaining-hard)

‚äĘ‚ąė evolve(explain, concept‚Üítext)
  through collect-explanations, deepen
  until collect-explanations‚Üíleaf-score ‚Č• 9
  max 3

  -- Each iteration: explain the concept ‚Üí assess which terms are hard ‚Üí
  -- spawn explainer cells for hard terms ‚Üí collect results ‚Üí if any
  -- sub-explanations still use hard terms, deepen further.
  -- Recursion depth bounded by max 3 and by the comprehension oracle:
  -- the explainer template marks still-hard = false when its explanation
  -- uses only simple terms, terminating that branch.
  --
  -- Oracles on `explain` are aspirational under ‚äĘ‚ąė ‚ÄĒ they describe the
  -- target quality. The `until` condition (leaf-score ‚Č• 9) is the actual
  -- convergence gate. Oracle failures feed back as context for improvement.
  --
  -- spawn-explainers uses `accumulate`: sub-explanations from previous
  -- iterations persist. The explanation tree grows monotonically.

‚äĘ format-output
  given collect-explanations‚Üífull-explanation
  given concept‚Üítext
  yield final-explanation

  ‚ąī Format ¬ęcollect-explanations‚Üífull-explanation¬Ľ as a clean, readable
    document explaining ¬ęconcept‚Üítext¬Ľ. Structure it as:
    1. The main explanation (for someone who knows related concepts)
    2. "Digging deeper" sections for each sub-concept
    3. A one-sentence summary a 10-year-old could repeat

  ‚ä® final-explanation starts with the main explanation
  ‚ä® final-explanation ends with a one-sentence 10-year-old summary
  ‚ä® final-explanation contains no unexplained jargon at any level
